data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new span conversions. When you write `array.Contains(num)`, overload resolution now prefers **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** over `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based calls, so compilation may succeed but the compiled/interpreted expression throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the call to bind to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the compiler from choosing the `Span`-based overload, keeping the expression tree representable. The same issue affects `Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` there too.
